    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130170\">Ryan Smith</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Working.20with.20Sylow.20subgroups.20in.20a.20simple.20case/near/533509598\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I'm finding it surprisingly hard to do the equivalent of \"let P be a sylow p subgroup of G of order p\".  The library has results that there exist a subgroup of order p^1 but not that it is a sylow p subgroup since that needs an extra property of maximality.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If you want an arbitrary Sylow <code>p</code>-subgroup you can use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Sylow.nonempty#doc\">docs#Sylow.nonempty</a></p>",
        "id": 533514567,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1754680427
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"130170\">Ryan Smith</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/Working.20with.20Sylow.20subgroups.20in.20a.20simple.20case/near/533509598\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I noticed that mathlib doesn't have the basic fact that for primes p and q all groups of order pq are solvable. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Actually, we have better than that: Every group of squarefree order is solvable. See <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=IsZGroup.of_squarefree#doc\">docs#IsZGroup.of_squarefree</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=IsZGroup.instIsSolvableOfFinite#doc\">docs#IsZGroup.instIsSolvableOfFinite</a> (the strongest statement we have is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=isZGroup_iff_exists_mulEquiv#doc\">docs#isZGroup_iff_exists_mulEquiv</a>)</p>",
        "id": 533515389,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Browning",
        "timestamp": 1754680932
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nice, we have Z-Groups. That proves the literal question at hand but the point was more \"how do I introduce a named sylow p group for G\" from the standpoint of a lean beginner. </p>\n<p>Or put another way, how do I explicitly go about using Sylow.nonempty for example? Maybe I'm just approaching it the wrong way and being too literal about translating English to lean by writing things like</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">have</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hP</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">P</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">P</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∈</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Sylow</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Sylow</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">nonempty</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Which is not at all well formed according to lean?</p>",
        "id": 533539621,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryan Smith",
        "timestamp": 1754695691
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>Sylow</code> is a type, which means you have objects of type <code>Sylow p G</code></p>",
        "id": 533540502,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1754696476
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In other words, you don't talk about subgroups being Sylow, instead you talk about Sylow subgroups</p>",
        "id": 533540584,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1754696547
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can still state \"the subgroup <code>P</code> is Sylow\" as \"there exists a Sylow subgroup which is equal (as a subgroup) to<code>P</code>\"</p>",
        "id": 533540676,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1754696618
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>you can obtain an arbitrary <code>p</code>-Sylow subgroup of <code>G</code> and name it <code>v</code> with</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">obtain</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">v</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Nonempty</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Sylow</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inferInstance</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 533540762,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1754696691
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for having the patience to answer simple stuff</p>",
